# riel-cursor-cli-developer-workflows

Use this rule as the canonical Cursor CLI developer-workflow dispatcher.

## Package

- Package id: `cursor-cli-developer-workflows`
- Workflow id: `cursor-cli-developer-workflows`
- Backend family: `cursor-cli-agent`
- Purpose: install the standard Cursor CLI developer workflow set and this
  single dispatcher rule.

Install the meta package instead of installing individual Cursor CLI developer
workflow packages by hand:

```bash
riela package install cursor-cli-developer-workflows --pre-install-check
```

For user-wide access:

```bash
riela package install cursor-cli-developer-workflows --user-scope --pre-install-check
```

## Dispatch

Before invoking a workflow, choose the narrowest matching workflow:

- Design-document authoring or refinement:
  `cursor-cli-deepdesign`
- Default non-trivial implementation work:
  `cursor-cli-design-and-implement-review-loop`
- Explicit Claude Fable 5 implementation-review variant:
  `cursor-cli-fable-design-and-implement-review-loop`
- Small code or documentation changes under a clear path:
  `cursor-cli-simple-work-package`
- Complete active implementation plans:
  `cursor-cli-impl-plan-completion-loop`
- Review and improve recent changes:
  `cursor-cli-recent-change-quality-loop`
- Broad or duplicate-scavenge refactoring:
  `cursor-cli-refactoring-divide-and-conquer`
- One read-only refactoring slice review:
  `cursor-cli-refactoring-slice-review`
- Source-code security review, deterministic scans, or security fixes:
  `cursor-cli-source-security-check-loop`
- Background task queue/watchdog work:
  `cursor-cli-task-watchdog`
- SolidJS website build/review/snapshot work:
  `cursor-cli-website-builder`
- Scoped adversarial implementation review loop:
  `cursor-cli-adversarial-implementation-review-loop`

Do not select hydra variants from this rule unless the user explicitly asks for
a hydra workflow and that hydra package is installed separately.

## Standard Runs

Design:

```bash
riela workflow run cursor-cli-deepdesign \
  --variables '{"workflowInput":{"feature":"Describe the feature to design.","targetDesignDoc":"design-docs/specs/design-example.md","constraints":["Design documentation only."],"acceptanceCriteria":["Deep review has no high or middle findings.","Broad review has no high or middle findings."]}}' \
  --output json --no-auto-improve
```

Default implementation:

```bash
riela workflow run cursor-cli-design-and-implement-review-loop \
  --variables '{"workflowInput":{"requestedBehavior":"Describe the requested behavior.","targetFeatureArea":"Describe the affected area."}}' \
  --output json
```

Small work package:

```bash
riela workflow run cursor-cli-simple-work-package \
  --variables '{"workflowInput":{"targetDirectory":"path/to/dir","requestedChange":"Describe the small change.","acceptanceCriteria":["Review has no high or middle findings."]}}' \
  --output json --no-auto-improve
```

Security check:

```bash
riela workflow run cursor-cli-source-security-check-loop \
  --variables '{"workflowInput":{"targetPath":".","runNetworkAudits":"false","maxFindings":50,"constraints":["Do not stage, commit, or push unless the user explicitly asks.","Do not revert unrelated dirty worktree changes.","Keep fixes narrowly scoped to verified security findings."]}}' \
  --output json --verbose --no-auto-improve
```

## Scope Rules

- Respect user instructions that forbid workflow use, commits, pushes, network
  audits, or broad refactors.
- Preserve dirty worktree changes that are unrelated to the chosen workflow.
- Prefer the meta package for installation so this rule cannot reference
  uninstalled standard Cursor CLI developer workflows.
- If a listed workflow is unexpectedly unavailable, run
  `riela package status cursor-cli-developer-workflows --output json` and
  reinstall or update the meta package before falling back.

## Verification

After changing this package or dispatcher rule, validate from the
`riela-packages` repository root:

```bash
bun .agents/skills/riela-package-release/scripts/update-package-digests.ts cursor-cli-developer-workflows
task check
```

For installed user-scope packages, verify visibility with:

```bash
riela package status cursor-cli-developer-workflows --scope user --output json
riela workflow validate cursor-cli-developer-workflows --scope user
```

Expected output from the meta workflow is a JSON payload listing this dispatcher
rule and the standard Cursor CLI developer workflow package ids.
